    "markdown": "## MRI Scan of Tongue Overview\n\n### What the test checks\n- Maps tumour size, depth and spread\n- Shows lymph-node involvement\n- Differentiates cancer from benign lumps, cysts or infection\n### Why choose Cadabams Diagnostics\n- 3T MRI + specialised head-neck coil\n- Sub-24-hour report turnaround\n- Online booking, digital reports, and transparent pricing\n\n## Risks & Limitations of the MRI Scan of Tongue\n\n### Contraindications\n- Pacemaker / defibrillator (most models)\n- Cochlear implants, neuro-stimulators\n- Certain aneurysm clips\n### Claustrophobia considerations\nMachine bore is 60–70 cm wide; exam lasts 20–40 min. Open MRI or mild sedation can be arranged on request.\n\n## List of Parameters Considered During the MRI Scan of Tongue\n\n- Tongue thickness and symmetry\n- Depth of invasion (DOI) – key cancer-staging metric\n- Signal pattern: solid vs. necrotic\n- Lymph-node size, number and extracapsular spread\n- Involvement of floor of mouth, mandible, neuro-vascular bundles\n\n## When to Take Test\n\n- Staging malignant lesions (TNM classification)\n- Pre-surgical mapping – save critical nerves and vessels\n- Post-treatment follow-up – separate scar from recurrence\n- Evaluation of tongue-tie or implant planning (selected cases)\n\n## Benefits of an MRI of Tongue Scan\n\n- Zero radiation – ideal for children, young adults and serial scans\n- Multi-planar views – true 3-D understanding\n- High soft-tissue contrast – detect 2 mm lesions\n- Same-day digital report – faster therapy decisions\n\n## Illnesses Diagnosed with MRI Scan of Tongue\n\n- Tongue squamous cell carcinoma (90% of tongue cancers)\n- Benign tumours – granular cell tumour, schwannoma, lipoma\n- Vascular malformations & cysts\n- Abscess, cellulitis, non-infectious inflammation (e.g., sarcoidosis)\n\n## Preparing for MRI Scan of Tongue\n\n- Fasting 4 hours if contrast is planned; water is allowed.\n- Remove all jewellery, hairpins, hearing aids.\n- Inform staff about pregnancy, allergies, prior contrast reaction.\n- Bring previous scans/CDs for comparison.\n## Pre-requisites\n- Written prescription from ENT / oncologist / physician\n- Recent kidney function test (Creatinine/eGFR) within 4 weeks if gadolinium is expected\n- Diabetic patients on metformin may need to withhold drug on the day of scan.\n## Best Time to Take the MRI Scan of Tongue\n- Early-morning slots minimise waiting and claustrophobia.\n- Avoid acute throat infections – motion artefacts from swallowing.\n- Women in first trimester may defer unless urgent.\n## Eligibility\n- Adults of any age\n- Children ≥5 years (younger kids need sedation)\n- Pregnant patients – non-contrast MRI only when benefits outweigh risks\n## Procedure for Taking an MRI Scan of Tongue\n1. Change into metal-free gown.\n2. Lie supine; head-neck coil positioned like a helmet.\n3. Foam pads minimise movement.\n4. Contrast injection (if ordered) via IV line.\n5. Scanner table moves in; you hear knocking sounds – ear-plugs provided.\n6. Stay still; occasional breath-hold commands.\n7. Total table time: 20–40 minutes.\n8. IV line removed; dressing applied.\n9. You may leave immediately unless sedated.\n## Caution Before Taking the Test\n- Remove credit cards, phones – magnet can corrupt data.\n- Notify technologist about tattoos, permanent eyeliner (some contain iron).\n- Renal impairment? Contrast dose is adjusted or withheld."
